        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(agents): strip null-valued optional args from MCP tool calls",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nLLM-generated MCP tool call arguments often contain `null` for unset optional parameters. Some MCP servers (e.g., awslabs eks-mcp-server) treat JSON `null` differently from an absent key — coercing `null` to `\"\"` and causing spurious failures. Other MCP clients (Cursor, Claude Desktop) already strip null keys from arguments before sending.\n\nThis fix addresses the problem at **two layers**:\n\n1. **Validation layer** — `packages/llm-core/src/validation.ts`: `coerceWithUnionSchema` now prefers exact type matches over coercion. For `anyOf [{type: \"string\"}, {type: \"null\"}]`, `null` naturally matches `{type: \"null\"}` and is returned as-is without entering the string coercion path that would convert it to `\"\"`.\n\n2. **Runtime boundary** — `src/agents/agent-bundle-mcp-materialize.ts`: As defense-in-depth, null-valued keys are stripped at the `createExecute` boundary before `callTool` receives them, matching the behavior of other MCP clients.\n\nNot modified: MCP SDK transport layer, JSON-RPC serialization, non-object input paths, resource/prompt utility tools.\n\n## Real Behavior Proof\n\n**Environment**: Vitest unit tests.\n\n**Proof scripts**:\n- `packages/llm-core/src/validation.test.ts` — test \"preserves null in anyOf [{type: string}, {type: null}] without coercing to empty string\"\n- `src/agents/agent-bundle-mcp-tools.materialize.test.ts` — test \"strips null-valued optional arguments from MCP tool calls (issue #96716)\"\n\n**Negative Control** (before fix): `coerceWithUnionSchema` tries `{type: \"string\"}` first -> `coercePrimitiveByType(null, \"string\")` returns `\"\"` -> validator accepts `\"\"` as a valid string -> union returns `\"\"`. By the time `createExecute` runs, the value is already `\"\"`, so a `v !== null` filter misses it entirely.\n\n**After fix**:\n- Validation: `{insight_id: null, cluster_name: \"testenv\"}` -> validates to `{insight_id: null, cluster_name: \"testenv\"}` (null preserved) ✅\n- Runtime (defense-in-depth): `{insight_id: null, cluster_name: \"test\"}` -> callTool gets `{cluster_name: \"test\"}` ✅\n- `{cluster_name: \"test\"}` (no nulls) -> callTool gets `{cluster_name: \"test\"}` (unchanged) ✅\n\n**Untested**: Real MCP server integration (requires running MCP servers).\n\n## Regression Test Plan\n\n```\n$ pnpm vitest run packages/llm-core/src/validation.test.ts src/agents/agent-bundle-mcp-tools.materialize.test.ts --run\n✓ |unit| 3 passed (3)\n✓ |unit-fast| 14 passed (14)\n```\n\nAll 17 tests pass. No other files modified.\n\n## Root Cause\n\n### Issue #1: Validation-layer anyOf coercion order\n\nIn `coerceWithUnionSchema()` (`packages/llm-core/src/validation.ts:207`), union members are iterated in order and each member applies coercion before validation. For `anyOf [{type: \"string\"}, {type: \"null\"}]` with `null` input, the `{type: \"string\"}` branch coerces `null` to `\"\"` via `coercePrimitiveByType` *before* the `{type: \"null\"}` branch is ever reached. Since `\"\"` passes as a valid string, the union returns `\"\"`. Only an exact-type-first ordering guarantees that `null` finds its `{type: \"null\"}` match before being corrupted by a sibling branch's coercion.\n\n### Issue #2: Runtime-layer unconditional forwarding\n\nIn `materializeBundleMcpToolsForRun`'s `createExecute` callback, raw (or post-validation) input is passed directly to `callTool` without normalization for null-valued optional arguments. This is the last line of defense; without it, any future change to validation that lets `null` through would still fail at the MCP server.",
        "branch": "fix/96716-mcp-strip-null-optional-args-clean",
